<subSubSection pageId="133" pageNumber="134" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="133.[151,1436,1122,2010]" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,468,1446,1471]" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among members of the 
<emphasis box="[756,873,1446,1470]" italics="true" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">Fundextra</emphasis>
group, similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2011" box="[1079,1201,1446,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="133" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifunda">
<emphasis box="[1079,1099,1447,1470]" italics="true" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1115,1201,1446,1470]" italics="true" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">bifunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the plaque ratios, having P2 slightly wider than the plaque separation (ratios ca. 5/1/8/4 and 5/1/6/4 respectively). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2011" box="[1257,1435,1483,1507]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="133" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thola">
<emphasis box="[1257,1435,1483,1507]" italics="true" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">Hydraena thola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs dorsally from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2011" box="[398,522,1518,1542]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="133" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifunda">
<emphasis box="[398,418,1519,1542]" italics="true" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[436,522,1518,1542]" italics="true" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">bifunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the following characters: the frons is strongly microreticulate, the pronotal punctures are much larger than the frons punctures, the elytral discal punctures are subserial or random, and the pronotum has a macula (
<figureCitation box="[435,545,1590,1614]" captionStart="FIGURE 243" captionStartId="327.[151,250,1753,1776]" captionTargetBox="[280,1344,239,1706]" captionTargetId="figure-25@327.[224,1363,193,1732]" captionTargetPageId="327" captionText="FIGURE 243. Hydraena bifunda, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283890" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283890/files/figure.png" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">Figs. 243</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[559,605,1590,1614]" captionStart="FIGURE 247" captionStartId="330.[151,250,1739,1762]" captionTargetBox="[201,1382,205,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-29@330.[186,1401,193,1718]" captionTargetPageId="330" captionText="FIGURE 247. Hydraena thola, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283896" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283896/files/figure.png" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">247</figureCitation>
). In addition, the plaques are carinate only at the posterior extreme. The male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2011" box="[350,443,1627,1651]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="133" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thola">
<emphasis box="[350,370,1627,1650]" italics="true" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[386,443,1627,1651]" italics="true" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">thola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
distinctively differs from those of other members of the group (
<figureCitation box="[1177,1277,1626,1650]" captionStart="FIGURES 248–249" captionStartId="331.[151,264,1650,1673]" captionText="FIGURES 248–249. Aedeagi of holotypes. 248. H. receptiva. 249. H. thola." pageId="133" pageNumber="134">Fig. 249</figureCitation>
). The prosternum, meso- and metaventrites, and the complicated leg chaetotaxy of the male protibia are illustrated with SEMs (
<figureCitation box="[159,323,1698,1722]" captionStart="FIGURES 376–381" captionStartId="367.[151,264,1650,1673]" captionTargetBox="[169,1417,196,1626]" captionTargetId="figure-26@367.[167,1420,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="367" captionText="FIGURES 376–381. Scanning electron micrographs of H. receptiva (376–379) and H. thola (380–381)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284015/files/figure.png" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">Figs. 380–381</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[334,380,1698,1722]" captionStart="FIGURES 382–387" captionStartId="368.[151,264,1650,1673]" captionTargetBox="[184,1402,196,1625]" captionTargetId="figure-28@368.[181,1405,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="368" captionText="FIGURES 382–387. Scanning electron micrographs of H. bifunda (382–386) and H. thola (387)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284019/files/figure.png" pageId="133" pageNumber="134">387</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
